text.html: Dojo Has it Large in... Ladbroke Grove
text.text: Dojo Has it Large in... Ladbroke Grove

Welcome to West London’s cultural melting pot, where ancient Rastas and young Hugh Grant lookalikes stroll arm in arm and browse market stalls. Where legendary Trellick Tower headbutts the sky, watching over the neighbourhood with a keen eye: Ladbroke Grove, we reckon it’s about time we had it large, don’t you?

tip.text: We love this spot not just for the cheap coffee served in iconic tall glasses in little plastic cages; nor for the crisp natas with beautifully spiced custard that has only just set; nor for the shaded outside tables perfect for people watching. The real draw here is the palpable sense of energy in the room: older Portuguese women having a natter with their nata, the hiss of the coffee machine and the barks of the servers all becoming a rolling laid-back buzz that consumes and comforts you all at once. It’s very popular amongst locals, so you may have to wait for a seat - but once one becomes available feel free to plonk it down at any table outside and you’ll be greeted with smiles and nods in true continental fashion.

text.text: Most W10 natives will concur that despite its unglamorous appearance, Lisboa Patisserie is the place for a coffee and a cake. It’s hard to miss the strong Portuguese influence on the Golborne road, so listen closely and follow the accents to this gem. We really can’t keep our hands off those cheeky natas (custard tarts), whilst streetside seating means you can sip and bite while partaking in the most apt of Golborne Road activities: people-watching in true continental fashion.
Best for... cultured cookbooks and a cheap ‘n’ cheerful luncheon

tip.text:
You don’t last 33+ years in the same spot if you haven’t got something about you. The first shop to import and stock cookbooks from overseas, Books for Cooks has managed to amass a somewhat cult following among Ladbroke Grove locals. Mosey in either side of lunchtime and find yourself in a tranquil space: all manner of rare and out of print editions are available here.

Lunch is what makes this place tick: every week chef Olivia flicks through a cookbook in the shop and curates a menu. Lunch is served at 12 but arrive at 11:45 to secure a seat: 3 courses for £7, or 2 for £5 - expect it to be a heaving, healthy and hearty affair, cooked with market veg and organically sourced meats.

text.text: We have a lot to thank Heidi for - in founding Books for Cooks she paved the way for the importing of cookbooks from abroad, which naturally means us Brits started to expand our culinary horizons (never a bad thing). Even more exciting is the daily dining on offer - recipes chosen from the brilliant and obscure selection of cookbooks housed here, prepared with delicious and healthy ingredients - and it’s actually cheap (!).
Best for… browsing: bits, bobs and bites to eat

tip.text:
Iconic, bustling and colourful, Portobello Road Market is a true testament to the history and people of London. Although the area’s gentrification over the past decade or so has seen a shift in the vibe towards the more upmarket, it remains a wonderful and worthy destination.

Crazy market day is Saturday: expect flocks of tourists seeking out the blue door from ‘Notting Hill’ and a motley crew of Portobello’s eclectic characters busking, conversing and wandering about. Arrive hungry and have your pick of the vying vendors, from paella to pancakes, and explore the shops and stalls at your leisure. Whether you’re after classic vinyl, antique jewellery, vintage clothing or that ephemeral “je ne sais quoi,” this famous and historic market is the perfect place to look. Look out for the Moroccan fish stall on Golborne Road - it's killing it.

text.text: There are markets, and then there are markets. While London is lucky enough to boast a fair few famous ones, there’s a reason Portobello Road Market will get bells ringing in heads worldwide: it’s like London’s left lung - that important. Whether you’re into people watching, window shopping or bargain hunting, this just has to be the go-to place. There is so much to explore, taste and experience on Portobello that it’s doubtful one trip will suffice.
Best for… a landlocked booze cruise

tip.text:
You might be forgiven for thinking you’ve stepped into a Hobbit’s tavern here: the miniature doors and quirky booths in this local boozer make for a baffling entrance at first. This is all indicative of the pub’s character, where you’ll frequently find seasoned locals rubbing shoulders with West London’s young and beautiful. The beer garden out back is huge and well furnished, perfect for a spot of good conversation (with humans or dogs as it happens).

The Earl of Lonsdale is a Samuel Smith pub, which is definite cause for celebration - it means pints in the £3-4 ballpark, a rare sight in LDN these days. Pub grub is available but nothing to write home about, though on Portobello a square meal is never difficult to come by.

text.text: The Great British public do like a bevvy or five, so where better to start than a great British public house? A higgledy-piggledy interior makes for a cosy experience, perfect for holing up when it’s nippy outside - lovely. The Earl of Lonsdale will help you get bladdered on the cheap so you can splash your cash on all that stuff you saw on the market but were too sober to buy - also lovely. Go on then...

tip.text:
Lord knows we love an ocakbasi, and Fez Mangal is the best in the west. Slap bang in the bustling heart of Ladbroke Grove, this is a lively and loud kebab house in the classic mould, with an open grill licking that lamb, beef and chicken - tender cuts that are then supplemented with beautifully fresh salads, soft pittas and subtly flavoured rice.

It’s a BYO affair and there aren’t many places to eat this well for so cheap in these ends, hence the queues you’ll spot come Friday or Saturday evenings. But those queuers are right - this one is made for booze-aided meals on the weekends when all that’s on your mind is getting good and full.

text.text: Everyone knows that the people of Turkey excel at grilling meats, so you won't be too shocked to hear that Fez Mangal is an excellent place to get nice and full. Tuck into the rich lamb shish or go all out on the Special Mix (£21 for 2) and then end things with a cheeky baklava for that burst of nutty sweetness. Plus it’s BYOB, so you can get merry on your own (cheap) terms.
Best for… breakfast, brunch and bubbly baristas

tip.text:
Locals make the daily breakfast pilgrimage here for a reason: it’s damn worth it. Delicious paninis, huge and hearty salad bowls, eggs benedict, homemade pastries, seasonal soups and all that good stuff. Go on, gather with the Golborne Road gang on a shared table and chin wag over the daily papers - on a bright day nothing beats sitting out front and taking in all the colours and smells of the area.

These guys aren’t messing with their coffee either: beans from Butterworth & Son, new baristas trained by a man from the company himself, brewed by weight. If the above doesn’t convince you that they look after their customers, they gift panettones to their regulars every christmas.

text.text: You know the saying ‘early bird catches the worm’? Well, in W10 the worm local birds are catching every AM is a breakfast from this cosy spot, be it a deep bowl of salad or the Full English type shebang with an Italian twist (think pancetta and ciabatta). Whether you like seeing others or being seen by others the seats out front are the best people-watching spaces in this ‘hood for sure.
Best for...stocking up on Spanish staples

tip.text:
This Spanish Mecca has been serving hungry expats and paella-philic Londoners since it opened in 1957 - and is known to be the largest Spanish grocery store in the Big Smoke.

This is the best place to stock up on Spanish staples like smoked paprika, olive oils, picante sauces - and more varieties of rice, pasta, and cheese than you can shake a churro at. Speaking of churros: pop in and chill out over Spain’s best doughy dessert with some excellent coffee. But don’t go home without browsing the meat counter, where you can scoop all the cured ham and sausages your carnivorous heart desires. It’s like a fiesta in your mouth.

tip.text:
Bringing Nordic tradition to London, Kell and Jacqueline Skatt have already showed us the light with their hair salons. Now they turn their hands to eateries. While they may be jacks of many trades they are also masters of many trades - Snaps & Rye is a simple yet smart invention - serving danish pastries, traditional Danish Smørrebrød on homemade rye bread and snaps.

They might be killing it in the lunch game but Snaps and Rye are dishing up dinners Thurs - Sat, and with a weekly changing set menu you're unlikely to get bored of the offerings anytime soon.
